Homework #5: Using a pretrained neural network

  1. Install and load the torch and torchvision packages.
library(torch)
library(torchvision)
  1. (1 point) Use the tiny_imagenet_dataset method to download a tiny version of the ImageNet dataset and name the dataset train_ds. Modify the template code as needed. Explain in your own words what the transform argument does. (When you finally knit this Rmd file, you may need to set download=FALSE rather than download=TRUE)
train_ds <- tiny_imagenet_dataset(
  getwd(),
  # set this to download = TRUE the first time you run this code
  download = FALSE,
  split="train",
  transform = function(x) {
    x %>%
      transform_to_tensor() %>%
      transform_resize(c(224, 224))
  }
)
  1. (1 point) Create a vector train_subset_ind containing the index of all observations in train_ds with class labels 1, 2, or 3. The class labels are stored in the targets attribute.
train_subset_ind <- which(train_ds$targets %in% c(1,2,3))
  1. (1 point) Create a subset of the original dataset composed of only observations with labels 1, 2, or 3 using the dataset_subset method and the vector train_subset_ind from question 3.
train_small <- dataset_subset(train_ds, train_subset_ind)
  1. (2 points) Randomly select 20 images from the dataset and visualize them. To do this, create a data loader with batch size 20 with shuffle=TRUE and name it train_dl_shuffle. Read the first batch of data from train_dl_shuffle and use the plot_images function to plot the images.
train_dl_shuffle <- dataloader(train_small, batch_size = 20, shuffle = TRUE)
batch_1 <- train_dl_shuffle$.iter()$.next()
plot_images(batch_1)

  1. (2 points) Create a new data loader for train_small that does not shuffle the data. Set the batch size to the maximum batch size. Name this new data loader train_dl.
train_dl <- dataloader(train_small, batch_size = 500)
  1. (3 points) Load a pretrained ResNet-18 model using the function model_resnet18 with pretrained=TRUE. Name the pretrained model pretrained_resnet. List the types of layers used in ResNet-18.
pretrained_resnet <- model_resnet18(pretrained = TRUE)

The layers used in the ResNet-18 are a 2-dimensional convolutional layer, a 2-dimentional max pool layer, and 4 sequential layers (1, 2, 3, and 4) containing two 2-dimensional convoluctional layers each. Layers 3 and 4 have a downsample sequential layer that both also contain 2-dimensional convolutional layers. A final average pool is performed.

Extracting features using a pretrained neural network

  1. (1 point) Our goal is to train a new model using the extracted features by ResNet-18. We’ll use the penultimate layer as the extracted features. To get extracted features, replace the last layer in pretrained_resnet with an identity module. That is, set the fc attribute in pretrained_resnet to a newly created identity module using the nn_identity function.
pretrained_resnet$fc <- nn_identity()
  1. (1 point) Set the pretrained ResNet-18 model to evaluation mode by calling the eval method of the pretrained_resnet object.
pretrained_resnet$eval()
  1. (1 point) Read the first batch of data from the data loader.
b1 <- train_dl$.iter()$.next()
  1. (2 points) Feed this batch of data through our (modified) pretrained network pretrained_resnet to get the values of the penultimate layer. What is the dimension of this output? Print the embedding for the first observation.
output <- pretrained_resnet(b1[[1]])
dim(output)

Training a model using extracted features

  1. (2 points) Create a data frame with the embeddings from ResNet-18 and their corresponding class labels.
df_embed <- as.data.frame(as_array(output))
df_embed$class <- as_array(batch_1$y)
  1. (2 points) Split this data so that 4/5 of the data is used for training and 1/5 of it is used for testing.
rnd_idx <- sample(seq(nrow(df_embed)), size = ((4/5)*nrow(df_embed)))
df_embed_train <- df_embed[rnd_idx,]
df_embed_test <- df_embed[-rnd_idx,]
  1. (2 points) Fit a random forest for this multiclassification problem using the training data. Use the default hyperparameter settings.
rf_model <- randomForest(x=df_embed_train[,-c(513)], y=factor(df_embed_train$class),
                         data = df_embed_train)
  1. (1 point) Evaluate the random forest model on the test data. What is the accuracy of this model?
preds <- predict(rf_model, newdata = df_embed_test)
mean(df_embed_test$class == preds)
## [1] 0.4
